= Witnessing the thoughts, witnessing the witness 

Let's utilize any stillness, and self liberation that has taken place, and go into the various levels of zoom, the aspects of our perspective. So typically the egoic structure is married to the thoughts or the emotions, or both. That means "I'm thinking right now", "I need to figure this out," and "what do I do?", and oh, "are you talking to me?" Yes, and you can talk, but you still have it... you've captured some kind of thought proliferation, something's on your mind. "I'm thinking". So the egoic structure is attached to that thinking, and whether you call it cognitive fusion in cognitive science, or if you call it binding in the dharma, you are bound to the thoughts, you see. Making sense, right? The mechanics of that.

Now please, I'm not saying you are bound to the thoughts, but this is the phenomenon of the appearance of sentient beings and confusion; so... are caught in distraction and fixation. So, one of the first steps is to become aware of thoughts. So before the thoughts were dragging the egoic pattern around---"I got to do this, I got to do that," "I got to..." you know, it's dragging us around. And this is most sentient beings who have not discovered any kind of meta-awareness or any alternative to being in thoughts. And thoughts are very, very safe then. We hold beliefs, we hold ideas, we hold convictions, and that becomes our safety.

And the egoic structure, like I said, is bound to that, is fused with it; so if you challenge a belief, you challenge me. You see how that works? If you disagree with my point, you are disagreeing with the very essence of who I think I am, because of that seventh manas-vijñāna, egoic pattern, that grabs everything. Technically speaking: misapprehending its own display, the mind misapprehending its own display, or apprehending in the first place is even appropriate to say.

And in this way, meditation, breath meditation, things like that, you become the witness. Right? So we all can have a thought right now: um... "I love apples." If we say "I love apples," there's some kind of witnessing that thought. There's a knowing of that thought. Anybody have a challenge to that? Can you witness a thought as you have it? Everybody? Excellent, that's a huge step. That is diffusion, and probably cause I'm here with a bunch of practitioners, so this is making sense.

Then the witness itself is also within awareness. You just told me it was. You just told me you were aware of a thought that you're having. So there was a feeling of me being aware of the thought "I love apples."

So there you have the sixth manas-vijñāna, the cognitive consciousness, conditioned consciousness. And you have the seventh egoic, the witness, the observer witnessing that thought, that cognition. If right now we say, get very elated---"I love apples,"---as we have that thought, that's also being apprehended by that egoic habit. 

So then we step back. Okay, now I can watch the thought "I love apples." Now I can watch that emotion that I'm having: "when I don't have apples, I'm upset." "When I have them, I'm happy." And then in this way, the witness with the awareness practice, because you get pointed to the nature of the whole thing, awareness is there through the witness and through the thoughts. Right? So you have the witness also. Now we can look directly into the nature of the witness and the thoughts, and both are empty; they're just within open mind.

If we say "I love apples," does that thought exist anywhere? Let's explore without thinking, without thinking, we're monobrained right now, monocognitive. The only thought we can have is "I love apples." Where is that thought? Look at where that is.

And now the watcher, the one who's looking, look at where that is. Ah, you see that opening? Even a little bit, you saw it. That opening is the emptiness of self. Now I can't speak anymore; I just emptied myself. But this is really---of course you can speak, I'm joking about that, but this is beginning to access the non-dual, spacious ineffability. Huh? And what's left? That's it. Once those main factors begin to soften up, once we diffuse and unbind from the thought and feeling entanglement, and then once that egoic structure construct starts to soften, there's a profound freedom there.

Now the senses are allowed to be wide open and self-liberate. The "I" consciousness has no basis anymore to land within awareness. Within awareness, the egoic construct has no basis, nowhere to land. So we can enjoy the play, the appearance of our body, of our mind, of these emotions without being bound to them. 

It's like having a bucket over us in the forest. You know, we were in this beautiful forest the whole time, but we had a bucket over us. Then one day the bucket tips over and we look around: holy moly, look where I've been the whole time; I didn't know I was here.

[To a fly] Oh, you leave my puppies alone; a fly trying to eat my dog. So, yes, this making sense, right? 

What do I mean by the bucket? It's all the thoughts we get stuck into within wide open infinite spaciousness, within the miraculous---Tathagata, right? We confine ourselves with a bucket of conceptual proliferation, fabrication, and distraction---that's our bucket. As long as we're distracted into stuff, we are missing the view. And notice, it's not that you never were in the view, you've always been in the view. That dang bucket.

Okay, making sense right? Everybody, any questions, comments, anything?

